            <fr:title text="slice of simplicial sets">slice of simplicial sets</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>
  Given a simplicial set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> and a vertex <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p : 1 \to  Y]]></fr:tex>, we define the <html:strong>slice</html:strong> simplicial set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y_{/p}]]></fr:tex> by the universal property that maps <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K \to  Y_{/p}]]></fr:tex> are in natural bijection with maps <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K^{\triangleright } \to  Y]]></fr:tex> from the <fr:link href="/forest/htt-000C/" title="cone over a simplicial set" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/htt-000C/" display-uri="htt-000C" type="local">cocone</fr:link> such that the cocone point is mapped to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
            <html:p>
  More generally, given simplicial sets <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X, Y]]></fr:tex> and a map <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p : X \to  Y]]></fr:tex>, the <html:strong>slice</html:strong> simplicial set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y_{/p}]]></fr:tex> is defined by the universal property that maps <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K \to  Y_{/p}]]></fr:tex> is in bijection with maps <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K \star  X \to  Y]]></fr:tex> such that the restriction <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X \hookrightarrow  K \star  X \to  Y]]></fr:tex> is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
            <html:p>
  Dually, we can define <html:strong>coslice</html:strong> simplicial sets <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y_{p/}]]></fr:tex> using cones <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K^{\triangleleft } \to  Y]]></fr:tex>. When <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> is an <fr:link href="/forest/htt-0001/" title="\infty -category" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/htt-0001/" display-uri="htt-0001" type="local"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\infty ]]></fr:tex>-category</fr:link>, we also call them <html:em>overcategories</html:em> and <html:em>undercategories</html:em>.
</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
